==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Muss
<hw>Muss</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF.
<ets>mousche</ets> a fly, also, the play called <ets>muss</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>musca</ets> a fly.]</ety> <def>A scramble, as when small objects
are thrown down, to be taken by those who can seize them; a confused
struggle.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Muss
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A state of confusion or disorder; --
prob. variant of <xex>mess</xex>, but influenced by <xex>muss</xex>, a
scramble.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Muss
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mussed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mussing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To disarrange, as clothing; to
rumple; -- often used with <ptcl>up</ptcl>; <as>as, the wind
<ex>mussed</ex> up my hair</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Muss</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Muss
<hw>Muss</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>mus</ets> a mouse. See
<er>Mouse</er>.]</ety> <def>A term of endearment.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <see>See <er>Mouse</er>.</see> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mussel</ent>⟦br⟧
